data.name: Label5.Text
data.value: The WHO's treatment policy, established in 2006 is to treat all cases of uncomplicated P. Falciparum malaria with artemisinin derived combinations (For example; artesunate-amodaqiaquine, artesunate-mefloquine, artesunate-pyronaridine, dihydroartmisininpiperaquinem and chlorproguanildapsoneartsunate) used to treat drug-resistant P. Falciparum. Unfortunately, as of 2009, a number f P. Falciparum-infected individuals have parasites resistant to ACT drugs. New drug treatment of malaria are currently under study because Plasmodium species continues to produce resistant strains that frequently spread to other areas. One Promising drug class under investigation is the spiroindolones, which have been effective in stopping P. Falciparum experimental infections.
